title: ELM327 ODB2 scanner casing with reset button

description.text:
Recently, i bought a cheap OBD2 scanner for my car with bluetooth connection.
It's the cheapest one on ebay right now for about 3.50 USD

search ebay for "ELM327 V2.1 OBD2 Bluetooth Scanner"

With this, your smartphone running the Torque app (or another OBD2 app) you can
view various realtime data from the vehicle, view error codes and reset error states.

I wanted to leave the device plugged in to the car, but because de device is always
supplied with 12V, even if the car is parked, the module keeps drawing 33mA current.
This cheap one does not seem to have a sleep state.
(note when transferring data, the amperage rises to 65mA max)

I've seen some solutions on the net to hack the OBD2 connector in the car, to make it
suppy the 12V from the accessories so it's only on when you turn the key.
This can be very tedious to do depending on make and model of your car because the OBD connector is mostly hidden somewhere under the dash.
But why alter the vehicle when hacking this module is so simple!?
You only have to cut pin 16 which goes to the PCB and solder a wire to the PCB.
That wire can be connected to anywhere behind the dash.. simple!

I randomly experienced some losses in the bluetooth connection, so i want to add a simple reset button. When using a "push to break contact" button in the power line, the module resets and in mather of seconds, the connection is restored.

Note; you can also alter the ODB2 adapter and only add a toggle on/off switch to it, without an external 12V supply wire, just make sure you don't forget to switch it off when you park..
(Yes, this can drain your car battery in a few days if the battery is a small one which is
not in a very good condition)

I printed a simple casing for this OBD2 scanner which press fits over the standard casing.
I also drilled a hole above each of the three LEDs and glued in a piece of transparant
1.75mm filament. This way, the LEDS can be seen from any angle. Make sure to cut of the
filament straight with a razor.

title: Modular MTG Deck Box with integrated Life Counter

description.text:
This is a modular deck box for MTG. Each section can hold 60 cards (including sleeves) and has an extra compartment for life counters, tokens, chocolate bars ...

  • Base
  • Base (stackable)
  • Lid with integrated live counter
  • Removable tray for three D20s
  • Removable tray for tokens

On the bottom side of the lid is a life counter with 20 holes integrated. Just a use a match or anything else with a diameter of 3 mm. The row on the left has no particular purpose. You can count whatever you need to.

I'm not a big fan of hinges and fasteners, because mostly they work only moderately in my prints. Therefore I simply hold together the deck box with a nice rubber band.

This is my first attempt to design a three-dimensional object. So, it may not be perfect. The first testprint on my Lulzbot Mini went well anyway.

The tray for the dice is derived from a design by Graffitibatman (www.thingiverse.com/thing:1273582).

UPDATE: I added four more files for those who have difficulties printing the small framing overhangs on the bottom. Now you can print the stackable version of the box in two parts (MTG-Deckbox-Bottom-Stackable-GlueTogether-1.stl + MTG-Deckbox-Bottom-Stackable-GlueTogether-2.stl) and simply glue them together. Same goes for the lid (MTG-Deckbox-Top-GlueTogether.stl + MTG-Deckbox-Logo-GlueTogether.stl).

UPDATE: I added a removable tray for token with five pockets.

This is a holiday remix of my iPhone 4s Captured Gear Case http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:51560 It has a bat rivet, a Jack 'O Lantern large gear, and a hooded skull in the place of the captured gear.

I tried out several new techniques for this build: I printed the pumpkin and skull with multiple colors using the [email protected] capabilities of Sailfish firmware: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:32084 I used a revised Openscad script from my lithophane gallery thing to output a round STL and then I duct taped it to the inside of the ring gear using Makerware. (You may have some trouble slicing it) I painted the background scene with ABS slurry onto the glass before I printed the case on top. (This last one, I could have done better, but I was in a hurry!) For everything, I sliced with .2 layers, 1 shell, 100% infill.
For the pumpkin, use yellow for the bottom .6, orange until 1.2, and black for the remainder.
For the skull, use black until .4, then white for the rest.
The bat rivet replaces one of the larger rivets in the regular plate.

Do you have a cat? Does your cat also like to play with your 3D printed cast-offs? Then why not print something intended for your cat instead, and do it in style, with this voronoi cat toy.  
Ten times better than a bland, store bought toy and ten times cheaper too. There's almost no drawback.

Print. Glue. Play.  
It's that simple.  
The "cat toy cut" file contains all of the pieces you will need in one file. Alternatively, you can print "cat toy inner cut" and "cat toy outer cut" separately, to print the inner and outer balls separately.  
Clean your print as needed, acetone or glue the inner ball together and put it inside the larger ball before gluing that together.  
If your cat likes catnip (and you have some), fill the inner ball with catnip before gluing together for an even more enticing toy.  
One thing to bear in mind - The inner ball is quite small, and will very likely slice as a single walled object meaning it will be relatively delicate. Luckily, since it will be inside the larger sphere, it doesn't need to be very tough (or very perfect) so even a not-so-perfectly calibrated printer should be able to produce a working copy.

Long before the Millennium Falcon, though, there was another ship, and it was at the time the fastest ship in the galaxy...

UPDATE 2016-09-26:
I've decided to switch to off-the-shelf omni wheels, since I was unhappy with the traction from ninjaflex tires. I've uploaded the DesignSpark Mechanical drawings for these if anyone wants to continue iterating on this design.

This omni wheel is a design I'm working on for a BB8 build. It mounts directly to a servo horn (I'm using these nice metal ones: http://www.robotshop.com/en/hitec-spline-metal-servo-tapped.html) and is designed to be assembled with 4-40 hex socket head machine screws. The axles are LEGO Technic axles, 4 pegs long. Each roller is 2 parts with a hub and ninjaflex tires.

First test print of the hard parts came back pretty good, but I've adjusted the position of some of the screw holes to ease printing and assembly, and adjusted tolerances so that the ends of the rollers don't need to be sanded for smooth rolling. Rollers had to be drilled out with a 13/64" bit (as intended) so that they have nice smooth bearing surfaces.

Tire test is mostly positive. While ninjaflex isn't the most inherently grippy material, it does a lot better than naked PETG. Printed with 100% infill, the tires have just enough stretch to be forced over the roller wheels. I had layer adhesion issues which complicated things a bit, but this is only my second time trying ninjaflex, so I'm gonna give it another slow a little hotter and a little slower. One they're on the wheel, the tires really seem to stay centered well.

8x Omni Wheel Roller - Wheel

title: San Francisco Giants World Series Plaque

description.text: The concept of the project is to create a SF Giants 2010 World Series plaque. There will be two sheets of 3mm acrylic that you will glue together. I will be using the CNC laser printer to print this from Illustrator. On the front there will be a vector cut of the logo. This will be cut on black acrylic and then the inside logo cut out will be removed. The orange flurescent piece will fit through the logo and photos will be added behind it. For the back (separate sheet of acrylic) will have "San Franciso Giants 2010 World Series Champions". You will need a two 10x10 sheets of black acrylic for this and also one sheet of 10x10 of an orange flurescent for the front design. A clear 11x11 piece of acrylic is needed to be cut to place the pictures on. Before printing the design, I will make sure everything is centered and perfect in symmetry. The goal of my project is to make create a nice plaque for my dad and brother to have.

Front of Plaque
  • First find a logo on the internet, copy and paste in a 10 by 10 document in Illustrator.
  • Create a rectangle 9.5 by 9.5 and center the logo in the rectangle.
  • Make the logo a vector cut as well as the outside rectangle.
  • Add any finishing details you desire.
  • You are finished with the front of your plaque!
    • Cut out Logo
    In a new 10 by 10 document copy and paste the logo from the "front of plaque" file into a new file in order to just print out logo on acrylic. Middle of Plaque
    Vector cut a 9.5 by 9.5 clear 3mm acrylic sheet to add pictures too. This will be added between the front and back pieces. Back of Plaque
  • Create a 11 by 11 document in Illustrator. Create a 10 by 10 rectangle.
  • Use the text tool to print the text you desire.
  • With the symbol paint tool add a symbol or any other details.
  • Check over everything and make sure everything is centered.
  • You are completed the back of the plaque!

description.text:
If you want more information and to see it more closely, watch this video: https://youtu.be/Za5byBQs0I4

This is the sheath that goes along with the Master Sword I created here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1449187

I created this sheath in Fusion 360 along with the sword. I printed this on my Robo 3D R1 using Hatchbox White PLA. The settings I used for this are listed below. The whole thing took about 14 hours to print.

Print Settings:
Layer Height: 0.3mm
Infill: 20%
Supports: No
Raft: No

Post-Processing:
Step 1: Print and Assemble. Print all the pieces out and use the keys provided to position everything correctly.

Step 2: Glue. Use Super Glue to glue all of the pieces in place. Let them sit until the glue completely sets up. We let ours sits for several days.

Step 3: Hide the seams. We used Loctite repair putty and just smeared it on the seams in order to cover them up.

Step 4: Sanding. Sand any rough spots and make sure to get the repair putty sanded down flush with the rest of the sheath.

Step 5: Prime. Apply a couple coats of plastic primer, letting it dry completely after each coat.

Step 6: Paint the blue sections. We used an airbrush for this, but any painting technique can be used.

Step 7: Paint the gold. Again, any technique can be used, but we went with a small painting sponge to give it a cool texture and allow for easy coverage on these big areas. Just dip the sponge in the paint and dab it all over the areas you want to paint.

Step 8: Apply some sort of finishing coat to it in order to protect it from damage to the paint.

description.text:
PUT CANON LENSES ON YOU GOPRO!!!!

Remove gopro lens, Get a cheep lens and take apart to get the IR-Cut filter or get one to fint you canon lens.

Use a spring from ballpoint pen cut in half for lock spring.

The IR-Cut has nothing to do with the focus it only cuts out the IR light. You can use without this step the image will just be a little pink in sunlight..

Cheep Way With Less Cost.

You have to take the original gopro lens out and then either get a cheep replacement lens to take apart or take apart the gopro one. Take everything out of the original lens except the IR-Cut Filter (Glass that has like a red/blue reflection)
Leave just the IR-Cut filter and put lens back in properly or backwards (pictures are lens installed backwards.

Easy way With More Cost

You can also just get a IR-Cut filter for what ever size cannon lens you are using. I went with modifying the gopro lens so it would be there for all my cannon lenses.

description.text:
This is a slightly modified version of the HiTec Motor Controller case. Having had the screw holes and tabs get broken many times over the years, thought this would be handy to be able to replicate and replace the bottom half of the case. I've made a slight tweak so that the holes on the tabs are a bit smaller to work better with the 6-32 screws usually used to attach them. I invite folks to take the STEP file and do some remixing to innovate on new and better ways to connect these to robot chassis. Even though they're legacy, i'm betting there are still a lot of FTC teams still using them out there.

The top is split into two files because it made printing it a lot easier and i didn't see any real problem with doing it that way. Tried printing the top as one piece with supports and it didn't work well, but feel free if you so choose.

title: Mayflash Arcade Stick - TeensyLC Adapter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
If you have a Mayflash Arcade Stick, Windows 10, and Street Fighter V, chances are good that you now know the difference between DirectInput and XInput. I had already replaced almost all of the components of the Mayflash, so my solution was to rip out the guts of the controller and replace them with something more modern. Thankfully, Zack Littel has instructions on how to turn a TeensyLC into an XInput device.

This thing is a little adapter that lets you use the original screws and mounting location within the Mayflash to mount a TeensyLC board. This project assumes you removed the original logic board replaced only two of the top-row buttons. The adapter will mount in the space under the original (now-removed) "AUTO" and "CLEAR" buttons. This will eventually be covered by a decal.

You will need to cut out a bit of plastic from the Mayflash to make this work. The next time I have the guts of the controller opened, I'll take pictures of the interior modification necessary.

title: Flashforge Creator Pro Bed Level code

description.text:
Included with the Flashforge Creator Pro is "Plate_levelling.x3g" - I didn't like that this script doesn't actually position the extruder nozzle over the bed adjusters, and of course you can't edit it as its x3g. I run off an SD card, so using something like RepG/S3D etc to assist in the level was not for me.

I wrote this script as I wanted more control over the bed level cycle.

Both the x3g and the source g-code file are included. If you want to customize the leveling positions, just edit them in the g-code, and compile into x3g with ReplicatorG.

Note
1.This cycle is setup for touching off the nozzle on a standard .100mm thick piece of paper. If you use this with the included blue Flashforge sheet (.200mm thick) it will be wrong!
2.The attached calibration cube is just here because Thingiverse won't let me just upload code.
